# A02 Neural Network Zoo – CNN Cheetah

This project explores the Neural Network Zoo through a single selected model: CNN Cheetah. The goal is to explain what a convolutional neural network is, how it works, and why it is useful for image-based tasks.

## Overview

CNN Cheetah represents a convolutional neural network because cheetahs are fast at spotting patterns and making quick decisions, just like CNNs are fast at detecting visual features in images. In this project, I describe the structure of the network, the flow of data through its layers, and common real-world applications.

## What I Covered

- What a neural network is.
- The basic structure of a CNN.
- How convolution, pooling, and fully connected layers work.
- Why CNNs are effective for image classification.
- Real-world uses of CNNs in computer vision.

## Why I Chose CNN Cheetah

I chose CNN Cheetah because CNNs are especially strong at recognizing patterns in image data. This makes the cheetah a good fit for the model’s speed and visual pattern recognition ability.

## Project Files

This folder may include:

- Presentation slides.
- Written notes or reflection.
- Images or diagrams used in the assignment.

## Key Takeaway

This assignment helped me understand that deep learning models are not one-size fits all. CNNs are best for image-related tasks, and choosing the right architecture depends on the type of data and problem.
